But I don't think it will end up being feasible.  I am open to being proven wrong.\n\nMy primary concern is water use.  I expect water to become more valuable.  Any one installation, it won't be a factor, but it they are widely deployed, it will be very significant.  It can be less of a factor in very dense areas where the water will run off and can not be captured.\n\nA secondary concern is maintainability.  It's easy enough to resod a yard (after a drought, say), but replacing a roof is more difficult.  Even more so on a non-flat roof.  This would not be a factor on a trial installation, but would be a huge obstacle to scaling it.\n\nIf it is a rooftop garden, and can be harnessed for food production and recreation, that's different.
